===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''semen'' "to seem, befit, be becoming" from {{etyl|non}} {{term|sœma||to conform to, beseem, befit|lang=non}} from {{term|sœmr||fitting, seemly|lang=non}} from {{proto|Germanic|sōm-||}}, akin to Old Norse {{term|somi|sōmi|honor|lang=non}}, {{etyl|ang}} {{term|seman|sēman|to reconcile, bring an agreement|lang=ang}}, Old English {{term|som|sōm|agreement|lang=ang}}

===Pronunciation===
* (''[[Received Pronunciation|UK]]'' & ''[[General American|US]]'') {{IPA|/siːm/}}
* {{audio|en-us-seem.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|iːm}}
* Homophones: [[seam]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|copulative}} To [[appear]]; to [[look]] [[outwardly]]; to be [[perceive]]d as.
#: ''He '''seems''' to be ill.''
#: ''Her eyes '''seem''' blue.''

====Quotations====
* '''1813''' (14th C.): [[w:Dante Alighieri|Dante Alighieri]], ''The Vision of Hell'' as translated by The Rev. H. F. Cary.
*: He, from his face removing the gross air,<br>Oft his left hand forth stretch'd, and '''seem'd''' alone<br>By that annoyance wearied.

